Q1: Basic Customer Profiling using Hierarchical Clustering¶

Customers are the only entities that pay, hence all revolves around the customer. As a data scientist, your objective is to understand the customers who purchase goods from the "Mall" store. How can you get to know your customers and how could this benefit your company?

You are given the "MallCustomers.csv" dataset for this analysis. Start with the steps below, and feel free to research customer profiling online.

  1. Analyze, plot and discuss the data

  2. Use the "Annual Income (k$) ","Spending Score (1-100) " features, and build a hierarchical clustering model.

  3. Evaluate the model results and discuss the performance.

  4. Discuss other ways to evaluate the results of your model (not general comments, but specific to your results).

  5. Plot the "Annual Income (k$)","Spending Score (1-100)" and use your clustering model predictions to color the customers.

  6. Write a short summary of all your findings and your interpretation of the results.

Build Hierarchical Clustering Model¶

In [24]:
# Hierarchical clustering
selected_features = customer_data[['Annual Income (k$)', 'Spending Score (1-100)']]

linked = linkage(selected_features, method='ward')
In [25]:
# Plotting the dendrogram
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
dendrogram(linked, orientation='top', distance_sort='descending', show_leaf_counts=True)
plt.title('Dendrogram for Hierarchical Clustering')
plt.xlabel('Customers')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean distances')
plt.show()
In [26]:
# Plotting a truncated version of the dendrogram
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
dendrogram(linked, orientation='top', truncate_mode='lastp', p=20, show_contracted=True, 
           distance_sort='descending', show_leaf_counts=True)
plt.title('Truncated Dendrogram for Hierarchical Clustering')
plt.xlabel('Cluster Size')
plt.ylabel('Euclidean distances')
plt.show()

From the truncated dendrogram, cluster = 6 would be a proper number of clusters from the cutoff line between 8000-10000

Evaluate the model results and discuss the performance¶

In [31]:
# Using fcluster to form flat clusters from the hierarchical clustering
# We can specify the number of clusters directly
flat_clusters = fcluster(linked, t=6, criterion='maxclust')

# Adding flat cluster information to the dataframe
selected_features['Flat Cluster'] = flat_clusters
In [33]:
# Normalizing the data
data_normalized = normalize(selected_features[['Annual Income (k$)', 'Spending Score (1-100)']])

# Creating a DataFrame for the normalized data
normalized_df = pd.DataFrame(data_normalized, columns=['Annual Income', 'Spending Score'])

# Adding cluster information again
normalized_df['Cluster'] = flat_clusters

# Setting the index as 'Cluster: CustomerID' format
normalized_df.index = ['Cluster {}: CustID {}'.format(cluster, id) for cluster, id in zip(normalized_df['Cluster'], customer_data['CustomerID'])]

# Dropping the 'Cluster' column as it's now part of the index
normalized_df.drop('Cluster', axis=1, inplace=True)

# Creating the heatmap using clustermap
sns.clustermap(normalized_df, method='average', col_cluster=False, cmap='viridis')
plt.show()

The heatmap provides a visual representation of the hierarchical clustering results. Each row in the heatmap corresponds to a customer, labeled with their assigned cluster and CustomerID. The rows are ordered based on hierarchical clustering, grouping similar customers together.

  • The colors represent normalized values of Annual Income and Spending Score. Darker colors in the 'mako_r' color map indicate higher values, while lighter colors represent lower values.
  • The clustering on the y-axis (rows) is based on the similarity of customers' income and spending score, as determined by the hierarchical clustering model.

Other evaluation of model¶

In [34]:
# Calculating the cophenetic correlation coefficient
cophenetic_corr, coph_dists = cophenet(linked, pdist(selected_features[['Annual Income (k$)', 'Spending Score (1-100)']]))

cophenetic_corr
Out[34]:
0.7179298392392908

The cophenetic correlation coefficient for our hierarchical clustering model is approximately 0.718. This value indicates a moderate to high degree of correlation between the cophenetic distances and the actual pairwise distances in the dataset.

  • Since the coefficient is closer to 1 than to 0, it suggests that the hierarchical clustering dendrogram reasonably preserves the original distances between pairs of customers in the dataset.
  • This means that the clusters formed and their hierarchical relationships are a fairly accurate reflection of the true similarities and differences among customers in terms of their annual income and spending score.

Cluster visualization¶

In [32]:
# Plotting the clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Annual Income (k$)', y='Spending Score (1-100)', hue='Flat Cluster', palette='viridis', data=selected_features, legend='full')
plt.title('Clusters of Customers (Flat Clustering)')
plt.xlabel('Annual Income (k$)')
plt.ylabel('Spending Score (1-100)')
plt.legend(title='Flat Cluster')
plt.show()

Summary¶

There are six cluster mapping in the graph:

  • Low Income, Low Spending Score: One cluster likely represents customers with lower income and lower spending scores. This group might be more price-sensitive.

  • Low Income, High Spending Score: Another cluster shows customers with lower income but higher spending scores. These customers might be younger or more inclined towards impulse purchases.

  • Moderate Income, Moderate Spending Score: There appears to be one or more clusters in the middle range of both income and spending. These could represent the average customers.

  • High Income, High Spending Score: There is a distinct cluster for high-income, high-spending customers. This group is often the target for luxury and premium brands.

  • High Income, Low Spending Score: Some clusters represent high-income customers with lower spending scores. These individuals might be more conservative with their spending or looking for high-value purchases.

  • Special Group (Variable Income, Variable Spending Score): There might be a cluster or clusters that do not fit neatly into the above categories, indicating a group of customers with varied income levels and spending habits.

With six clusters, the analysis can cater to more specific marketing strategies, as it allows for a more granular understanding of different customer behaviors and preferences.
